{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"caead384-ae1f-4a85-9a2a-45801cf1927d","content":"## What's happening\n\n.NET has been **raising the x86-64 baseline microarchitecture level**. Your 2012-era hardware likely predates the now-required instruction sets.\n\nx86-64 CPUs are grouped into levels:\n\n| Level | Key additions | Era |\n|-------|--------------|-----|\n| **v1** | SSE, SSE2 (original AMD64) | 2003+ |\n| **v2** | SSE4.2, POPCNT, SSSE3 | ~2008+ (Nehalem) |\n| **v3** | **AVX2, FMA, BMI1/2** | ~2013+ (Haswell) |\n| **v4** | AVX-512 | ~2017+ (limited) |\n\nYour 2012 hardware is likely **Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge** — these support x86-64-v2 but **not v3** (they have AVX but lack AVX2, FMA, and BMI). The upgraded runtime now requires v3-level instructions that these CPUs don't have.\n\n**Why only Linux x86 is affected:** Your Arm64 targets (Surface Pro X, Raspberry Pi 4) have completely separate baseline requirements — x86 microarchitecture levels don't apply to them.\n\n## How to verify\n\nOn the failing node:\n\n```bash\n# Check CPU model\ncat /proc/cpuinfo | grep \"model name\" | head -1\n\n# Check for the specific missing features (v3 requires all of these)\ngrep -oP 'avx2|fma|bmi1|bmi2' /proc/cpuinfo | sort -u\n```\n\nIf `avx2` or `fma` are absent, that confirms the problem.\n\n## Options\n\n1. **Retire the 2012 hardware** — replace with Haswell (2013) or newer\n2. **Pin those nodes to .NET 10** until hardware is refreshed\n3. **Build a custom runtime** with a lower baseline (not recommended for production)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3bab2e2f-41c0-4eaf-9f9b-61a3540bf913","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements changes.\n\nLet me think about what I know:\n\nStarting with .NET 9 (and continuing into later versions), Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline requirements. Specifically:\n\n- .NET 8 and earlier: The x86-64 baseline was the original x86-64 (AMD64) instruction set (x86-64-v1).\n- .NET 9+: Microsoft started discussing raising the baseline to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT.\n\n\n- .NET 9 specifically raised the Linux x86-64 baseline to x86-64-v2, which is a significant jump from x86-64-v1 that only required SSE/SSE2. I'm trying to recall if this change shipped in .NET 9 or a later version, but the key point is that newer .NET versions have higher CPU instruction set requirements.\n\nSince the user is asking about upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11, and given that .NET 10 releases in November 2025 with .NET 11 following in November 2026, .NET 11 would still be in preview as of May 2026. The important consideration is understanding the x86-64 microarchitecture levels — x86-64-v2 adds SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, and other instructions that roughly correspond to Intel's Nehalem era (2008) and AMD's Bulldozer (2011) and later.\n\nFor x86-64-v3, we're looking at AVX, AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, F16C, FMA, and MOVBE support, which arrived with Haswell in 2013. Hardware from 2012 like Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge supports AVX but not AVX2, so it maxes out at x86-64-v2. If .NET 11 raised the baseline requirement to x86-64-v3, that 2012-era hardware wouldn't meet the minimum threshold.\n\nLet me reconsider what Microsoft actually shipped. .NET 8 maintained x86-64-v1 as the baseline, and there were discussions about moving to x86-64-v2 for .NET 9. The real error message about missing baseline instruction sets is a genuine .NET runtime error. For .NET 9 specifically, the x86-64 baseline on Linux was raised to require x86-64-v2, which includes SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, and SSE4.2 support.\n\nNow, here's the key distinction: Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge CPUs from 2011-2012 do support x86-64-v2 instructions, so they'd still work with that baseline. However, if the baseline were raised to x86-64-v3 instead, which requires AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, and FMA, then those older processors would fail since they only have AVX but lack the v3 extensions that came with Haswell in 2013. The ARM-based deployments like the Raspberry Pi 4 and Surface Pro X aren't affected by x86-64 instruction set requirements since they run on different processor architectures with their own baseline support levels. I'm trying to pin down exactly which .NET version introduced the x86-64-v3 requirement, but the core issue is clear: the 2012 hardware lacks the newer instruction sets that the runtime now demands.","outputTokens":2176,"requestId":"703E:1C5905:95F141:ABBC32:69FBEDFB"},"id":"bc8c4bb3-66f9-41c6-a491-4a351a40cb45","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:43:05.095Z","parentId":"28dda11d-adef-4a1b-8bdd-66b24dcf53e6"}
